Did you know Ohio State football's William "Big Bill" Bell was a star both on and off the field? Bell, who played for the Buckeyes from 1929 through 1931, earned All Big Ten and Honorable Mention All-American honors his final season. Off the field, he was a member of the African-American social fraternity, Alpha Phi Alpha, among other things. His senior year, the Upper Class Cabinet of the Ohio State chapter of the YMCA tapped Bell to lead a new committee on interracial relations. After his time at Ohio State, he went on to have a career coaching football and organizing physical education departments. Photo: The Ohio State University Archives

Statements on Mirror Lake tragedy

Statement from Ohio State University President Michael V. Drake: "We are heartbroken over this horrible tragedy. We have tentatively identified the young man as a student and are in the process of reaching out to his family. During this difficult time, counseling services will be made available throughout the holiday weekend for those who seek support," said President Michael V. Drake.

Statement from The Ohio State University: In spite of significant efforts taken to make this event a safer one, this tragedy has occurred. We must come together and acknowledge that while this is a student-led tradition that has been passed down through the years, we cannot risk another tragedy. University leadership strongly agrees that we will work with our campus community to end this annual event.

Omar Torres, an Ohio State scholarship student who joined the Army Reserves as a freshman, was called to active duty his second year and was killed in Baghdad in 2007. 

"Omar wore his heart on his sleeve and accepted anyone and everyone for who they were," his sister Oralia Torres-Mathew says. "He'd be so proud and honored that he would turn it around so others feel special, too. That's the type of person he was." 

For his service and dedication to our country, we honor him and other Ohio State veterans who died in service.

status_message: Oct. 9, 1965: TBDBITL plays "Hang on Sloopy" in Ohio Stadium for the first time. (Note: The crowd hasn't added O-H-I-O yet!) Director Charlie Spohn thought it would be fun to see the band transition from a ballerina dancing to classical music to a girl swaying to a popular rock song, "Hang on Sloopy." There were 83,700 fans in the stadium that day, including Spohn's wife, Dorothy. She says, "Rock 'n' roll changed the direction of the band. It was a sign that they were going to do things that were funny and entertaining." They still do today, gaining worldwide acclaim.

"As a student worker in Ohio State's dental clinic, it's a part-time job, and I work on setting up cubicles for patients and practicing dental students, dispensing dental instruments and making sure everything is safe and sterilized. But it's also been a really great opportunity to immerse myself in the medical environment to see if its something I'd like to continue pursuing as a career. I've learned so much from the full-time assistants who have taken me under their wings and given me the opportunity to learn and experience a lot of things I wouldn't have had any exposure to until dental school. And of course being around great faculty, residents and dental students, I've picked up on lots of technical terms and processes, tools, and course information - it's kind of like having a behind the scenes look at dental school, which at this point in my undergraduate career is so valuable." Emily Mumaw | Business finance | Second-year | Centerville, Ohio

"It was fun. It was a labor of love," John Tatgenhorst says of the arrangement he made of "Hang on Sloopy" for The Ohio State University Marching Band in 1965. He started composing music for the marching band when he was a student in the School of Music. His first contribution was "A Hard Day's Night"; his most enduring was "Hang on Sloopy." Tatgenhorst wrote it in about four hours after his mentor, Professor Charlie Spohn, made a late decision to include it in a band halftime show celebrating the arts on Oct. 9, 1965. "Sloopy was just something I enjoyed doing," Tatgenhorst says. "It's just luck that it caught on."

status_message: "I'm in an in vitro (i.e. preserved tissue and not live lab) Alzheimer's lab currently and I stain human brain tissue to look for different lesions in Alzheimer's, Parkinson's and other dimentia brain samples. I came into Ohio State wanting to do research because I had hoped to pursue my PhD in neuroscience. Well, after joining my lab last January, I fell in love with research and have decided to pursue my education in not only neuroscience, but also the research aspect of the field. Hopefully, my work will go onto furthering our understanding of the pathology of Alzheimer's as well as developing a way to diagnose patients while they're still living, since the only true way to diagnose Alzheimer's is with an autopsy." John Tatgenhorst '70 was honored by The Ohio State University Marching Band on Sept. 13, 2014. Tatgenhorst, a professional composer with clients like Coca-Cola and Warner Bros., was a percussion student when he arranged The McCoys' 1965 hit "Hang on Sloopy" for the marching band. He never expected it to become an Ohio State tradition that would endure for more than 50 years. http://go.osu.edu/hangonsloopy

Over the last 50 years, a simple rock 'n' roll song has become synonymous with Ohio State. While "Hang on Sloopy" topped pop charts at one time, it likely would have been forgotten had it not been for Ohio State students adopting it as their unofficial anthem. As Ohio Stadium prepares to rock again this fall, take a look back at the history of the song - from its roots as a rhythm and blues song from 1964 to the last-minute decision to include it in a halftime show in 1965 - with a special interactive experience. http://go.osu.edu/hangonsloopy

Throwback Thursday! "Hang on Sloopy" is a cover song of the 1964 rhythm and blues song "My Girl Sloopy." The Vibrations recorded it for Atlantic Records, and the song reached No. 26 on the charts in 1964. "My Girl Sloopy," with a Latin percussion section featuring timbales and tangos, sounds vastly different from its rock 'n' roll relative. Read more about the history of the Buckeye anthem: http://go.osu.edu/hangonsloopy

The Ohio State University Marching Band played "Hang on Sloopy" on Oct. 9, 1965 ‚Äì one week after The McCoys' version hit No. 1 on the pop charts. The band's halftime show that day was honoring the arts, and they formed a ballerina while playing Tchaikovsky's "Waltz of the Flowers" before dancing Watusi-style and playing "Hang on Sloopy." Director Charles "Charlie" Spohn said that the juxtaposition would amuse the crowds in Ohio Stadium, never realizing it would become a tradition at Ohio State. Public Safety Notice

The Ohio State University Police Division has been informed of postings to fantasy, role player game sites which reference a potential public safety threat of violence focused on a "cafeteria" today on the Columbus campus. We continue to investigate and are taking these posts seriously to the point of having extra police and security presence on and around campus dining facilities. We have the assistance of federal, state and local law enforcement agencies.

This information is being sent so that the university community is aware and to ask assistance in reporting any related suspicious persons or activity today or in the future. 

If you see something, say something - non-emergency Police line: 292-2121. As always, in an emergency, call 9-1-1.

Officers confirm a shooting involving three OSU employees, none of which were students. One employee is dead, two have been transported to the hospital.
